Former President Donald Trump on Nov. 13 blamed Senate Minority Leader Mitch McConnell (R-Ky.) after Democrats secured control of the Senate after winning races in Arizona, Nevada, and Pennsylvania.

â€œItâ€™s Mitch McConnellâ€™s fault,â€ Trump wrote on his Truth Social platform. â€œSpending money to defeat great Republican candidates instead of backing Blake Masters and others was a big mistake. Giving 4 Trillion Dollars to the Radical Left for the Green New Deal, not Infrastructure, was an even bigger mistake.â€

â€œHe blew the Midterms, and everyone despises him and his otherwise lovely wife, Coco Chow!â€ Trump added, referring to former Transportation Secretary Elaine Chao.

Trump-endorsed tech entrepreneur Blake Masters lost to incumbent Sen. Mark Kelly (D-Ariz.) in Arizonaâ€™s Senate race by more than 127,000 votes, or about 5.3 percent.

The Democrats will have at least 50 seats, after Sen. Catherine Cortez Masto (D-Nev.) won reelection by defeating Republican challenger Adam Laxalt in Nevadaâ€™s Senate race. So far, only one Senate seat has flipped, with Democrat Lt. Gov. John Fetterman defeating Republican candidate Dr. Mehmet Oz in Pennsylvaniaâ€™s Senate race. Fetterman will replace retiring Sen. Pat Toomey (R-Pa.).

The Georgia Senate race remains undecided, with a runoff election scheduled for December after neither Sen. Raphael Warnock (D-Ga.) nor Republican Herschel Walker secured more than 50 percent of the vote.

The GOP is still in the position to retake control of the House. Republicans have 212 seats and Democrats have 201, according to data from Decision Desk, which The Epoch Times uses in its Election 2022 map. It requires 218 seats to take control of the lower chamber of Congress.

In a separate Truth Social post earlier on Sunday, Trump shared an article titled â€œAfter Epic Failure, Growing Chorus Of Senators Signals Itâ€™s Time For McConnell To Go,â€ which argues that McConnell must be removed from the Senate Republican leadership.

â€œAgree with this 100%!â€ Trump wrote, referring to the article. â€œMitch McConnell is a disaster for the Republican Party and the Country.

â€œHe should have improved Infrastructure to fix it, not the Green New Deal, wrapped up like Infrastructure. He gave the Democrats 4 Trillion Dollars to throw out the window, and backed bad candidates like Lisa Murkowski,â€ Trump added.

The Federalist article, published on Nov. 11, said McConnell â€œsabotaged Republicans in the 2022 midtermsâ€ by â€œpulling spending from competitive GOP candidates such as Blake Mastersâ€ and spending money against Kelly Tshibaka in Alaska.

Trump-endorsed Tshibaka, a Republican who was a former Alaska Department of Administration Commissioner, has a 1.38-percent-lead (pdf) over incumbent Sen. Lisa Murkowski (R-Alaska). The winner has not been declared.

Senate Republicans are reportedly scheduled to hold leadership elections on Nov. 16. However, some are calling for the vote to be delayed until after the Senate runoff election in Georgia is completed.

â€œThink about it â€“ if we hold leadership elections on Wednesday, thereâ€™d be more campaigning done in a high-school class president election than in the most deliberative body in the world,â€ Sen. Ron Johnson (R-Wis.) wrote on Twitter. â€œIt is absurd. These elections need to be delayed.â€

â€œIt makes no sense for Senate to have leadership elections before GA runoff,â€ Sen. Ted Cruz (R-Texas) wrote on Twitter. â€œWe donâ€™t yet know whether weâ€™ll have a majority & Herschel Walker deserves a say in our leadership.

â€œCritically, we need to hear a specific plan for the next 2 yrs from any candidate for leadership,â€ Cruz wrote.

Sen. Josh Hawley (R-Mo.) and Senator-elect Eric Schmitt (R-Mo.) have already said that Republicans need new Senate leadership. However, Sen. Tom Cotton (R-Ark.) told CBS News on Sunday that he will back McConnell as Senate GOP leader.

A day before the midterms, Trump endorsed Sen. Rick Scott (R-Fla.) as a â€œlikely candidateâ€ for Senate Republican leader in an interview with Fox News Digital. Trump praised Scott as a â€œvery talented guyâ€ who is â€œhighly underrated.â€

The former president predicted Scott would â€œhave a lot of support.â€

Sunday was not the first time Trump commented on the midterm elections. On Nov. 9, he conceded that election results were â€œsomewhat disappointingâ€ but still a â€œvery big victory.â€

â€œWhile in certain ways yesterdayâ€™s election was somewhat disappointing, from my personal standpoint it was a very big victoryâ€”219 WINS and 16 Losses in the Generalâ€”Who has ever done better than that?â€ Trump wrote.

According to Ballotpedia, 17 Trump-backed Senate candidates, including Walker, won in the midterm elections, while 6 lost.
